05278nam a22007695i 9781501701535DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979687380  a97815017015357 a10.7591/97815017015352doi  a(DE-B1597)478537  a(OCoLC)967268041  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBX2330b.P78 2016 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a235.24092231 aPrudlo, Donald S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCertain Sainthood :bCanonization and the Origins of Papal Infallibility in the Medieval Church /cDonald S. Prudlo. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. “By the Authority of Blessed Peter”: Making Saint- Making -- t2. “They Trust not in the Suffrages of the Saints”: Saintly Skirmishes -- t3. “That the Perversity of Heretics Might Be Confounded”: From Practice to Theory -- t4. ”Hark, Hark, the Dogs Do Bark . . .”: The Assault on Mendicant Holiness (1234–60) -- t5. “That God Might Not Permit Us to Err”: The Articulation of Infallibility in Canonization -- t6. Sancti per fidem vicerunt regna: “The Saints, by Faith, Conquered Kingdoms” -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe doctrine of papal infallibility is a central tenet of Roman Catholicism, and yet it is frequently misunderstood by Catholics and non-Catholics alike. Much of the present-day theological discussion points to the definition of papal infallibility made at Vatican I in 1870, but the origins of the debate are much older than that. In Certain Sainthood, Donald S. Prudlo traces this history back to the Middle Ages, to a time when Rome was struggling to extend the limits of papal authority over Western Christendom. Indeed, as he shows, the very notion of papal infallibility grew out of debates over the pope's authority to canonize saints.Prudlo's story begins in the twelfth and thirteenth centuries when Rome was increasingly focused on the fight against heresy. Toward this end the papacy enlisted the support of the young mendicant orders, specifically the Dominicans and Franciscans. As Prudlo shows, a key theme in the papacy's battle with heresy was control of canonization: heretical groups not only objected to the canonizing of specific saints, they challenged the concept of sainthood in general. In so doing they attacked the roots of papal authority. Eventually, with mendicant support, the very act of challenging a papally created saint was deemed heresy.Certain Sainthood draws on the insights of a new generation of scholarship that integrates both lived religion and intellectual history into the study of theology and canon law. The result is a work that will fascinate scholars and students of church history as well as a wider public interested in the evolution of one of the world’s most important religious institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCanonizationxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristian saintsxCultxHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aPapacyxHistoryyTo 1309. 0aPopesxInfallibilityxHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi